segments.text: You were born and where you spent most of your young life.
Well, my full name is Ray Ben Nesbitt.
It's not Raymond, it's not Benjamin, because we couldn't afford all the extra letters that were required for that.
So it's very, and that's why I said Billy Don and this was JC.
And that was the way you went by.
You went by double names when I was growing up.
But I was born on a dairy farm right outside of Marshall, about five or six miles.
in a community that was known as Bear Bottom until 1957.
And they wanted some government money to put in a water system, so they changed it to Nesbitt, Texas.
Did they really?
Yeah.
And that's spelled B-E-A-R, Bear Bottom.
It's B-E-A-R. Bear Creek runs into Cypress about seven miles northwest of Marshall.

they didn't think that bare bottom sounded like a good name to go to the government so it's now nesbit texas and my kids stole one of the city limit sign and it's in my den and it says nesbit texas population 376. so it's not a very big place in fact it's probably around 250. you still have relatives yeah but none of my direct family or my uncles and aunts and all those
on my father's side are all dead, and my parents are both dead.
On my mother's side, there are still her sisters and brothers that live in that same community.
We have our own cemetery, Nesbitt Cemetery, established in 1846.
So your family got into that area in that, really, in that time?
Yeah.
The two twins, Nesbitt twins, came down to fight the Mexicans about 1836 and 1842.
From Tennessee?
Well, they actually, this group came from Kentucky, and their cousins were in Tennessee.
And the ones that came down from Kentucky, their mother...
delivered Abe Lincoln and Abe Lincoln's mother delivered the twins, the two Nesbitt twins, Robert Nesbitt and Nathan Nesbitt.
And they came down to fight the Mexicans and then they went back up, but then they offered them some land, you know, a league of land for, you know, fighting.
So they came down and then
Following the Civil War, they invited their cousins from Tennessee to come down, and that's when my grandfather came down.
He was Benjamin Franklin Nesbitt.
So the Nesbitt group has been in that area for 150 years or so.
That's an early settlement in that part of the country.
So you grew up on a dairy farm.
On a dairy farm.
And you learned to milk cows.
Learned to.
I had to milk cows.
My father ran a dairy for a while down in Plaquemines Parish, Louisiana.
I know where that is.
Before I came along, or about the time I came along, I guess.
That's the worst job you could possibly have.
It's seven days a week, and it starts very early, and it goes very late, with a lot of time off in between.
And you went to school at Marshall High.
Well, we were milking cows in those days by hand because of the...
Rural electrification didn't come to that area until about 1944.
So through the third grade... Did you use a cream separator, too?
Yeah.
Through about the fourth or fifth grade, we still were using kerosene lamps until 44 from 33, 11 years, fourth or fifth grade.
So I went to school in Marshall by bus, as everybody did in those days, and...
I didn't take any science in high school at all.
I didn't take chemistry, physics, or any of those because I took agriculture.
It was a hell of a lot easier.
And I didn't have to have any homework.
And to get up and milk cows every morning and afternoon, I didn't want to have any homework to mess with.
So as I said, then when I decided
The last thing I wanted to do was to grow up, I mean, to stay on the farm.
So I was going to get away from there.
My dad went through the ninth grade, eighth grade, and my mother went through the ninth grade.
And his objective in life is he's going to send all five of his kids to college.
And he said, even if you had to sell all the land he had.
You were there when I did that little talk up there, and he achieved his objective.
In fact, my last sister graduated in the summer of 59, and he died in January 60.
Is that right?
Yeah.
That was a common objective.
That's quite an accomplishment, too, to have done it.
You have brothers and sisters?
I have four sisters.
Four sisters, and you are the male of the family.
I'm the only one of the male group.
I had to get a boy dog.
I have three daughters.
So my mother's first 11 grandkids were all girls.
Is that right?
Yeah, we just didn't have any males in the family.
And you went to Texas A&M?
Yep.
Why?
Because you wanted to be in agriculture?
First of all, it was the cheapest place to go.
Okay.
And my only contact of any school was through the agricultural teacher.
He was a graduate of A&M.
That's right.
And I had been to all the fat stock shows down in Houston.
You and Ray had a parallel career.
I won the dairy judging contest at the Houston Fat Stock Show in 1948.
But I decided that farming wasn't for me.
And so when I got to A&M, the first thing I did is I went over.
I was visiting.
It was in the spring of 52.
And there were a couple other friends of mine who were either freshmen or sophomore there.
So they invite us down for a weekend.
And there were several others who went down there.
Because as it ended up, I think out of our class, we must have had 10 or 11 boys from Marshall that went to A&M.
So I went over to the placement office and I said, who made the most money of the graduates last year?
You really did this?
How serious?
And who did you talk to in the placement office?
Mr. Heaton was running it, but I was talking to one of his secretaries.
He was still at Heaton.
Yeah, Heaton was a good guy.
Homer Lloyd Heaton, he was a good guy.
So I asked, who made the most money of the graduates last year?
And they said, well, the chemical engineers.
And I said, fine, I'm going to be a chemical engineer.
And they looked at my record, and they said, well, you can't.
I said, why is that?
You haven't had any chemistry or any physics.
You've had no sciences.
Well, I said, give me a chance.
So they forced me to take summer school.
I had to go to summer school to take chemistry the first summer.
before they would agree that they let me into chemical engineering.
Needless to say, I took chemistry and I graduated in three years with a degree in chemical engineering.
Got married the day after I got out of high school.
Oh, did you?
Okay.
I'm glad you asked that question.
My wife went to A&M.
So you went through A&M as a married student?
Yeah.
That's why I was in a hurry.
Yeah, I can understand that.
That's very formidable.
That's very good.
They told me I couldn't do it, but... Did you work, have scholarships?
I borrowed money to go to school, and so it was very cheap to go to school in those days.
It was $42 a semester, including all fees, and it included an annual and tickets to the football games and health insurance.
That was all for $42 a semester.
Rented an apartment in...
College View, C12W.
It cost $31.50 a month, all utilities paid.
So... Yeah.
And your wife went to school, too?
No, she was not allowed to go to school.
That's what I was, that was my question.
She was not allowed to go to school.
And you finished in three years, so that's 55.
I started in the summer of 52, and I graduated in the spring of 55, and I only had to take 14 hours last semester to graduate.
I have got approval to take...

like uh physical chemistry and chemical engineering and thermo before i had taken physics and so i took them simultaneously although physics is a prerequisite for those two courses in those days and most of the professors you had in chemical engineering were in 200 andrews and lindsay lindsay used to teach uh he taught about two courses uh while i was there he
He taught one sophomore course, which was sort of an introductory type chemical engineering, and he taught a senior course, which was, I would call it, what I call practical chemical engineering.
Remember?
It was... No, because one of them was that, you know, you had a...

One of the quiz questions I remember, you've got a pile of sulfur that's so many tons, and you've got a sulfuric acid plant that's so far away, and how would you go about designing a process for moving the sulfur to where you use it in the process?
And the only thing that was acceptable in those days was a black and a wheelbarrow.
That was the only answer to the question that he would accept.
I talked to his son, Hugh.
Lindsay interviewed him, and he was talking about his dad grading papers, and he said he had one paper, and he still remembers his dad doing that.
The student made such a high grade
that his dad sat and was worried with that paper apparently all night long because he just don't do that.
He just wasn't right, you know, and he really worked it through.
Yeah, he's in the book here.
He said he made a hundred, and he was determined to find something wrong with it.
Yeah, that's interesting.
Andrews was your favorite.
He was the best real teacher of any of the group.
I had Bishop, I think, in one class.
People liked Bishop.
He was likable, but he wasn't that good.
I don't think I ever had Holland.
I don't think I ever had Harris.
His son was in our class, Don Harris.
He graduated with us.
He has a grandson.
Is that right?
See this one right here?
William Donald Harris Jr.
Okay, let me know.
He was in the classroom.
Of this group of 23, how many do you think ended up working for Exxon?
Thirteen.
Well, no, you had DuPont Shell, you had Carbide, you had Lubrizol, you had Diamond Alkali, you had...
Houston Ship Channel was pretty well faster than companies in those days, but six of the 23 ended up there.
Now let me ask you, while you were in school, did you feel like you were being pointed in any special direction as a chemical engineer, in petroleum, in...
I don't know what.
Well, at one time, I was going to take a joint degree in petroleum engineering and chemical engineering.
Okay.
So I more or less... You assumed you would go into petroleum industry somehow or in some capacity.
Was that pretty much the assumption within the department?
Would you say the Department of Chemical Engineering in those days was definitely pointed toward petroleum?
Or was pointed... Not definitely.
I don't want to be too strong.
No, because, you know, we used to go on these field trips and we went on...
a trip in 54 and we went to Sea Drift and we visited Carbide's new facility, just started up.
They had an ethylene oxide glycol, steam cracker, ethane cracker, and they had a polyethylene.
Then they took us to Dow and we visited their magnesium operations.
At that time, they were using these aircraft engines for generating power.
Remember those old rotary engines?
You probably don't remember that.
We also visited the Alcoa plant at Rockdale.
Is that where it was?
Yes.
We visited Humboldt Oil and Refining Company, and we visited Texas City Carbide.
Now, who took you on those trips and stuff?
Well, actually, in those days, the bird dog was Holland.
He was the one that... Was he doing that?
He was doing that.
He was given that responsibility.
Let's put it that way.
I guess the same thing is true for every spring and every fall.
I forgot which one.
Senior class in the fall, or vice versa.
Junior class in the fall.
One time, a senior fire department had three days, and what do y'all call it?
Oh, yeah, we didn't have any.
And you met at these plants.
Yep.
And you were on this channel.
Yep.
And there'll be some visits to the plant.
And those visits sort of influenced your direction, or...?
Do you remember anything special about them as a consensus?
Or a better understanding of the business you were going to get into?
I had a better understanding of the type of company I would like to work for because I remember the guy who was the recruiter at Carbide.
His name started with an I, an Italian name, but Ignatius or something like that.
I remember the manager at Seadrift.
Marvin Eccles.
He was a fairly recent A&M graduate, I guess, when he became manager of the Carbide plant.
But as a result, it told me who I wanted to interview.
And I interviewed Shell, Carbide, DuPont, and Humble.
And I worked the summer of 54 for Humble.
And so when I interviewed, I had four offers.
I could have gone to UOP, but
I said, there's no way.
Don't make me an offer.
I'm not going to Venezuela.
I had no desire to want to go to, I forgot the name of that town.
Exxon had a great big refinery in Aruba at the time.
It was a part of the Creole operation.
But UOP, that's where they started their new employees, some of these startup sites.
So I got four offers, and the lowest offer I got was from Humble.
And that's the one I accepted.
And I accepted it because the previous summer I worked for a guy named George Mason.
And to me, he was a very, very impressive guy.
And he was the type of guy I wanted to work with.
And so that's why I accepted the job there.
Because of your previous summer?
Previous summer, he'd been my boss.
So I get there in 55, and in 56, he leaves the company and goes to work for Tenneco.
And he became the number two guy in Tenneco before he retired.
I still see him around here.
He's quite an individual.
Now, so you're coming to Houston, your first job.
What happened is I went to talk to Lindsey.
And another perception of all this was that when you got out of school, you would stay in Texas.
Yeah, that's what I was going to tell you.
I went to see Lindsey and talked to him about a job, which, you know, get a little counseling from him.
And he said, well, I'd go to work for any of the four except one.
He said, don't go to work for Hummel.
And I said, why?
Why do you say that?
Oh, he said, they have this damn practice school down there, and they weed out 10, 20 percent of their people every year, you know, and they've been sort of rough on some of my students.
And I said, well, gee, my reasoning for wanting to go was to take practice school.

I said, I've rushed through college, and I would like to get something on what I call applications that would, it was a 13-week course, you know, eight hours a day, five days a week, or 12 hours a day, five days a week, and all of the unit operations and the specific processes that we had at Baytown.
So I said, I looked on that as a sort of opportunity to sort of
put in place how you can go from the theoretical to the practical.
And I said, I was leaning toward accepting the job with Humble.
I said, first of all, that's the only one of this group where I don't think I'll ever have to leave the state of Texas.
And what did he say to that?
He didn't say anything.
You know, he's advised on this one, how he was in the Texas locations.
And then after a couple of years, you can move them out.
Wherever you want them.
Now, so you're coming as what?
What capacity?
What is your job when you're first hired?
Junior engineer.
That was the lowest.
And at the time, I went to... And now are you in the office or the field where they're putting you?
Well, we had the old main office building there at Baytown.
It's been torn down since then.
But they had what was called Tech Service Division.
and it consisted of 85 chemical engineers, all chemical engineers.
At Baytown, we said there's chemical engineers and there's other engineers.
It was the way we used to put it.
And the chemical engineers made up the tech service group, and the engineering department consisted of all other engineers.
Of that group, when I went to work there,
The first level of supervision was called a section head.
And the most recent promotion to section head was a guy by the name of Glenn Wilson.
And he had been out of rice since 1936.
So he had been with the company 12 years before he made section head.
It was a group of pretty good quality because they'd been taking bottom 10% out for years and years and years.
That's the only way they could continue to bring in new blood.
And so you get rid of eight to ten people a year and you've hired ten or twelve.
Some of those had been Lindsey's people and he didn't like that.
And he didn't like that.
Hamp Oliver was one in the class before me.
Pete Gola, Jerry Jenkins.
I don't know if you remember these guys or not.
I don't know Jerry Jenkins.
Pat Souther.
But he didn't like the idea of the weeding people out like that.
He didn't think that was very good.
But I thought it was a pretty good approach.
But you did go through the practice school, and then you were put in the Tech Services Division.
I was in the Tech Services Division, and you started in June.
And practice school started the first of September and went through Christmas.
And the bottom guy in the class left.
It was only 10 of us, so even 10% won.
And so with that type of weeding out process and not forcing people to move to other parts of Standard Oil in those days,
We had a pretty high-class organization.
From that organization came Pervin and Gertz.
They started consulting Pervin and Dallas.
The Pace Company, Payne, Askey, Service, and Eckholm.
Is that where Pace is?
Okay.
Yeah.
Payne, Askey, Service, and Eckholm.
Bonner and Moore.
You ever hear of Bonner and Moore?
I think I have.
plus a whole bunch of people.
One of them was the chairman of Continental, came out of that tech service group.
The vice president of acquisitions for W.R. Grace came out of that group.
George Mason was the number two guy in Tenneco.
Excuse me, six of you who went into that were Aggies.
No.
No.
There were, in that particular class, there were only...
One, two, three of us.
Now, where are most of the other hirees coming from?
Well, one of them went on to graduate school.
Two of them went to graduate school, John Frondley and Bob Zumwalt.
They both got a Ph.D. and then came to work for Exxon.
So of the group that went to work, we had, there were three of us.
Jack Spellings.
Spellings?
Jack Spell.
Spell.
He was Don Harris's best friend.
They grew up in Bryan.
Yeah, Jack Spell and myself and Tom Campbell all started immediately.
John Frondlick and Bob Zumwalt came in after they finished graduate school and Jim Knudsen went to work for Carbide
and worked for Carbide for two years, and then came to work for Exxon.
So that was the sixth out of the 23.
And where is Exxon hiring from?
The rest of the people in your tech services division came from where?
Any concentration?
Oh, we had... Rice, LSU, MIT... From everywhere you can think of.
We had MIT, we had Texas University, LSU, Tulane, we had...

delaware wisconsin minnesota michigan yeah obviously there's an obvious concentration uh rice well let's see one was from harvard business school one was a phd out of texas one was from oklahoma state one was from university of oklahoma
One was from Louisiana Tech, and one was from Arkansas, and the rest I was staying in.
Now, when you start your first job and you're looking at your peer group there, how do you stack up with that bunch in terms of your own comfort index, in terms of your training?
You were comfortable with what you had been through.
Oh, I thought I was as well-trained as they were.
I think that A&M's always had a very good reputation for undergraduate training.
Always have.
And I think they do a good job in that area.
And of course, from the standpoint of what the state is expecting, that's exactly what they want.
Sure.
That's exactly what they wanted.
You have to.
Yeah.
So you're going to be in the Tech Services Division for how long?
Well, I figure I've got to stay there 12 years in order to get promoted.
So I started off working in the chemicals area because I was working on a butadiene unit and a butyl plant.
We had just acquired the butadiene and the butyl plant from the federal government in March of 1955, right before I showed up.
And at that point in time, we were dehydrogenated normal butylenes.
We had a process where we took the C4 strain, we used acid extraction to get isobutylene, and that went to the butyl rubber plane.
We had an extractive distillation process where we
separated the butylenes from the butanes, okay?
It was, we called it the GK unit, I don't know.
It was a, I forgot what kind of extractive or azeotropic type, just a what?
And then we take the butylenes and dehydrogenate them, you know, over the old shell 105 catalyst, which is an iron oxide, I think.
and using very high temperature steam, 1400 degrees or something like that.
I remember that it was anytime you heard that there was a steam leak at the dehydro unit, you didn't walk.
What you did is you got a pole and put a rag on the end of it because you cannot see 1400 degree steam.
And therefore, when the little handkerchief disappeared, you knew where the leak was.
So you're going to be working on your 12 years in that unit.
Well, I figure I am.
But in about three years, I'm a section unit.
And the first job they gave me was there was a guy from Arkansas that they wanted me to get rid of.
That was the first assignment.
So you get started with learning how to deal with people.
And I guess about...
But you're still in Houston.
Still in Baytown.
Still in Baytown.
And so this is about 1959, I guess, 58 or 59 that I become a section head.
And then, you know, things rock along.
And this guy, George Mason, who went with Tenneco, calls me up and invites me over to see him.
And he offered me the job as chief engineer for Tenneco Orkin.
So I went and visited Chalmette, Louisiana, I think it is.
And I told him I'd give him an answer on Saturday.
On Friday,
They reorganized the old tech service division and reorganized the whole refining operation.
They split off chemicals from petroleum, where we made two separate entities, had a chemical plant manager and a refinery manager.
And I was given the job of technical superintendent for chemicals.
So I called Mason up to talk to him.
I decided I was going to accept the job.
I called him up and he said, I withdraw my offer.
He said, you're going to stay.
That's what he told me, you're going to stay.
That was nice.
That was nice of you to do that.
We've made good friends over here.
So Exxon now really is defining its mission.
I was on the committee that split chemicals from the oil side.
We divided up all the assets and things like that.
And this was in 59?
And I had been on the committee to divide up assets.
They reorganized in 62, and that's when I became the superintendent
Technical Superintendent for Chemicals.
And then in 63, I got moved to New York, working for NJ Chemical Company, running the projects in Long Range.
NJ, E-N-J-A-Y, just to make sure.
That's the way all of this, you know, like SO.
SO2.
SO is Standard Oil, S-O.
And NJ, New Jersey.
It was E-N-J-A-Y.
So this one is S-O and this one is N-J.
That's where those two trademarks came from.
So now I'm working in New York, living in Connecticut.
And that was in 63 and in 68.
Now you're primarily, are you moving more and more in?
